{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To prevent identity theft, no ID can be a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie containing all final IDs, no leaf node is an ancestor of another leaf node. The goal is to minimize the total bits added to make all strings 'uniquely identifiable' via their prefixes.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction_expert",
      "instructions": "Design an efficient algorithm to insert all N bitstrings into a Trie. For each node in the Trie, track whether it represents the end of an original ID and the number of original IDs that pass through or end at this node. The total number of nodes can be up to 10^6, so use an adjacency list or array-based Trie to avoid recursion depth issues in Python."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_optimization_expert",
      "instructions": "Given the Trie structure, determine the minimum number of bits to append. The rule is: if an original ID ends at node U, no other ID can have U as a prefix. This means if node U is a terminal node for an original ID, all descendants of U must be 'blocked' or the ID at U must be extended. However, the problem asks to extend the IDs. Formulate a greedy strategy: for every node that is a terminal node of an original ID, we must ensure it is not a prefix of any other ID. This is equivalent to saying that in the final Trie, every original ID must end at a leaf node. Calculate the minimum bits needed by traversing the Trie and determining how many bits must be added to each path to ensure no terminal node is an ancestor of another terminal node or a non-terminal node that becomes a terminal node."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will combine the Trie structure from helper 1 with the greedy cost calculation from helper 2. The core logic is: for each original ID, if it is a prefix of another ID, we must extend it. The total cost is the sum of the lengths of the extensions. The optimal strategy involves identifying nodes in the Trie that are 'terminal' and ensuring they are not ancestors of other terminal nodes by extending them to the nearest available leaf or unique path."
}

